WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.460
 Now that we've talked about forms a bit,

00:00:01.460 --> 00:00:04.040
 I want to talk a little bit about security in forms.

00:00:04.040 --> 00:00:06.080
 I want to talk about a security issue

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:10.920
 called Cross Site Request Forgery, or CSRF.

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:15.920
 So the idea of a CSRF attack is that a rogue site,

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:18.720
 it has to do with cookies and how cookies get sent to site.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.360
 So let's say you're logged into a MySite,

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:25.000
 and a rogue site generates a page that's going to post.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.520
 And on every form, you can post to a site

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:28.960
 other than the one it came from.

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:32.840
 And so if I can get data that I want to send

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:36.500
 to the legitimate server, the rogue site can set up a post,

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:39.440
 and then if I can mention you to hit the button,

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:42.120
 then it will grab the cookie and send it

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:44.600
 to the legitimate server that you're already logged into,

00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:46.800
 and perhaps do something dangerous.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:49.460
 And so the rogue server doesn't need to know the cookie,

00:00:49.460 --> 00:00:51.920
 the rogue server just needs to convince you

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:56.920
 to click on a rogue form to send to the request server.

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:02.280
 So the defense for CSRF is don't be confused with Session.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:05.300
 It is going to use Session.

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:08.240
 We're going to grab another large random number,

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:10.080
 and we're going to call it the CSRF token,

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:12.240
 and we're going to stick that in the Session.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:15.340
 And then what we do is every time we send a form out

00:01:15.340 --> 00:01:16.780
 that's coming from our server,

00:01:16.780 --> 00:01:20.520
 we add a little input hidden tag that has this CSRF token,

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:21.880
 and then when the post comes in,

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:25.760
 we check the CSRF token that's coming in in the post data,

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:28.160
 and then we check it against the one that's in the Session,

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:30.200
 and then rejects it if it doesn't match.

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:33.600
 So here's a picture of how this works, right?

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:36.400
 So we'll have a legitimate server, right?

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:38.920
 We're going to produce a page by the legitimate server,

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:42.100
 and it's going to post back to this same server.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:45.680
 The action is the URL to send the post data to,

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:49.680
 and we got some key value pairs and a submit button, right?

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:51.000
 So you hit the submit button,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.880
 and it's going to come back to the server.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:55.480
 Now one of the things that the browser is supposed to do

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:59.480
 is pull the cookies for that server and send it.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:02.420
 So it sends it both a post and the data,

00:02:02.420 --> 00:02:05.480
 but it also sends the Session ID cookie.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:09.900
 And then what happens is that the Django gets its hands on it,

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:12.280
 it looks up the Session ID, pulls it in,

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:14.840
 and notices that it's CSEV and I've been logged

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:19.440
 as an instructor, and then I can actually change this grade

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:21.900
 and set the grade, and it works.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:26.060
 Okay, now here is what happens when you get to a CSRF attack.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:33.340
 So somehow a page gets sent to the server, right?

00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:36.740
 Sent from a rogue server, and it just has this form.

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:38.860
 Method equals post, action equals DJ.

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:41.940
 It's not the action, it's going to a different place.

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:45.760
 And it puts sort of a new grade and then a submit.

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:49.400
 So what happens is this submit comes in,

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:53.180
 and the browser dutifully appends the cookie to it,

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:54.420
 and it sends it.

00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:57.340
 Now you had to be tricked into getting to this page

00:02:57.340 --> 00:02:59.860
 and sometimes tricked into submitting the page,

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:03.240
 but once the post comes in, it has legit cookie in it.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:06.560
 The cookie is used to look up the Session and reassociate it,

00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:07.800
 and we can check in the Session

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.760
 that the user is indeed logged in,

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:13.480
 and we'll let the thing set the grade to 1.0.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:15.680
 So this would be a way if you could convince

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:19.840
 a logged in instructor to run a post form that you created,

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:23.280
 you could basically change your grades.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:26.540
 So that's how it works, that's how a CSRF attack.

00:03:26.540 --> 00:03:28.720
 You have to be tricked twice first,

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:30.980
 but there's ways in JavaScript to make it

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:33.420
 so it's hardly noticeable that you get tricked.

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:37.420
 So if you do this with CSRF, the legit server

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:42.740
 basically adds another value, not the Session ID,

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:44.720
 but another value in the Session,

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:47.200
 which is a large randomly chosen number,

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:51.060
 and then when a page comes out, it's a legit page,

00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:53.860
 and it uses a type hidden variable

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:56.340
 and puts the CSRF value in.

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:58.180
 Now you hit the Submit button,

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:01.520
 and the CSRF is coming in as post data,

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:05.080
 the regular data, the grade data is coming in,

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.740
 and the browser dutifully appends the Session,

00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:10.940
 and so then using the Session cookie,

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:12.820
 it reassociates the Session, says,

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.520
 "Yup, you're C7, you're the instructor,

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.240
 "and the CSRF works, CSRF matches,

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:22.340
 "so let's go ahead and let you set the grade."

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:23.840
 So we let them in.

00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:28.100
 With the attack blocked, because the rogue server

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:32.760
 can generate a page, but it doesn't know what the CSRF is,

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:36.920
 so who knows what the CSRF is, so it generates it,

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:40.500
 maybe it can put a CSRF, but it doesn't know it,

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.200
 so then the post happens, and all the data gets gathered up,

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:47.100
 and so it sends the CSRF, but it's not the right CSRF,

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:51.800
 the Session ID is sent in, and so the Session is pulled in,

00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:53.820
 we know it's user C7, we know it's instructor,

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:57.540
 but we're gonna check to see if the CSRF matches,

00:04:57.540 --> 00:05:01.620
 and then it blows up, and so then you just refuse the post,

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:02.960
 probably log the user out,

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:05.440
 and then log some kind of a security error.

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:08.120
 So the idea is, is by having this little CSRF number

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:12.040
 in the Session, we can then take care of that.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:16.840
 So, like most things, Django comes out of the box

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:20.520
 with CSRF protection built in, just like the Session,

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:24.040
 we've got CSRF middleware just dropped in,

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.260
 and actually it works automatically,

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:28.040
 you don't even have to ask for it to work.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:32.220
 Once you have a Session, it starts putting out CSRF things.

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:33.420
 So up next, we'll talk about,

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:35.520
 now that we know the concept of CSRF,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:38.320
 we'll talk about how we're going to use CSRF

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:42.480
 inside of forms to implement sort of CSRF protection.

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:44.900
 (jazz music)

